    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-04-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-04-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="324"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d324">
                <head>324. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d324fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 726,
                        Country Files—Europe, United Kingdom, Vol. II. Secret. Sent for
                        action.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-04-10">April 10, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Your Position on British Entry into the Common Market</item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP_1">Rogers</persName> has sent you an urgent
                    memorandum (Tab A)<note n="2" xml:id="d324fn2">Not printed.</note> reporting
                    that, according to a British démarche at the State Department, President
                        <persName corresp="#p_PG_1">Pompidou</persName> is telling people that you,
                    in effect, do not favor early British entry into the Common Market.</p>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP_1">Rogers</persName> recommends that you
                    reiterate to <persName corresp="#p_BW_1">Brandt</persName>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d324fn3">West German Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_BW_1"
                            >Willy Brandt</persName> visited Washington April 7–11.</note> that our
                    support for strengthening and enlargement of the Common Market is
                    undiminished—the formula used in your foreign policy report to the Congress.</p>
                <pb facs="1018" n="979" xml:id="pg_979"/>
                <p>General <persName corresp="#p_WVA_1">Walters</persName>’ records of your talks
                    with <persName corresp="#p_PG_1">Pompidou</persName>
                    <note n="4" xml:id="d324fn4">See <ref target="#d141">Document 141</ref>.</note>
                    do not indicate that you said anything that would be inconsistent with giving
                    support to British entry into the Common Market.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Recommendation</p>
                <p>Consequently, I believe it would be desirable, if the opportunity arises in your
                    further talks with <persName corresp="#p_BW_1">Brandt</persName>, for you to
                    state that we remain in support of the Common Market and its enlargement.<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d324fn5">A handwritten note by <persName corresp="#p_HHR_1"
                            >Haldeman</persName> at the bottom of the page reads: “K—This arrived
                        for the Pres—<hi rend="italic">after</hi>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BW_1">Brandt</persName> had departed. H”.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
